2. Load the Yelp dataset¶

About the data ¶

  • The Yelp dataset has been updated for Yelp dataset challenge 7. There are plenty of interesting insightswe can draw from this dataset.
  • This set includes information about local businesses in 10 cities across 4 countries.
  • There is a good combination of reviews, business attributes, check-ins, and tips, and open the door to even more exciting research.
  • Each file is composed of a single object type, one json-object per-line.

Below are the files which are loaded and used for our recommender systems project¶

2.1 Load the checkin data¶

#### The json object looks like this : """ check-in { 'type': 'checkin', 'business_id': (encrypted business id), 'checkin_info': { '0-0': (number of checkins from 00:00 to 01:00 on all Sundays), '1-0': (number of checkins from 01:00 to 02:00 on all Sundays), ... '14-4': (number of checkins from 14:00 to 15:00 on all Thursdays), ... '23-6': (number of checkins from 23:00 to 00:00 on all Saturdays) }, # if there was no checkin for a hour-day block it will not be in the dict } """
In [3]:

d = list()

        d.append(json.loads(line))
checkin = DataFrame(d)

2.2 Load the business data¶

#### The json object looks like this : business { 'type': 'business', 'business_id': (encrypted business id), 'name': (business name), 'neighborhoods': [(hood names)], 'full_address': (localized address), 'city': (city), 'state': (state), 'latitude': latitude, 'longitude': longitude, 'stars': (star rating, rounded to half-stars), 'review_count': review count, 'categories': [(localized category names)] 'open': True / False (corresponds to closed, not business hours), 'hours': { (day_of_week): { 'open': (HH:MM), 'close': (HH:MM) }, ... }, 'attributes': { (attribute_name): (), ... },

In [7]:
def find_rest(a_list,x):
    res = [y for y in a_list if x in y]
    if len(res) >= 1:
        return True
    else:
        return False
In [8]:

restaurants = restaurants.drop('index',axis=1)

In [11]:
# The table has some columns which have a comlex json structure.
# Using the below fuction we can get various restaurant attributes from the attributes column.
def get_restaurant_attr(a_json,column):
    if column == 'Ambience':
        if column in a_json.keys(): 
            return sum(a_json[column].values())
    if column == 'Good For':
        if column in a_json.keys(): 
            if sum(a_json[column].values()) > 0 : return 1
            else : return 0
    if column == 'Parking':
        if column in a_json.keys(): 
            return sum(a_json[column].values())
    elif column in a_json.keys():
        return a_json[column]
    else:
        return 'N/A'

# Dropping unneccesary columns while createing SFrame to reduce load on the algorithm

df1 = restaurants_LV.drop(['attributes','categories','full_address','hours','latitude','longitude',\
                                             'neighborhoods','state','type','city','open'],axis=1).reset_index()
df1 = df1.drop(['index'],axis=1)

# Imputing missing values with mode before converting to SFrame

df1.Acc_credit_card = np.where(df1.Acc_credit_card=='N/A',False,df1.Acc_credit_card)
df1.Alcohol = np.where(df1.Alcohol=='N/A','none',df1.Alcohol)
df1.Ambience = np.where(df1.Ambience=='N/A',np.nan,df1.Ambience)
df1['Good For'] = np.where(df1['Good For'] =='N/A',np.nan,df1['Good For'])
df1['Delivery'] = np.where(df1['Delivery'] =='N/A',False,df1['Delivery'])
df1['Price Range'] = np.where(df1['Price Range']=='N/A',np.nan,df1['Price Range'])
df1['Take-out'] = np.where(df1['Take-out']=='N/A',np.nan,df1['Take-out'])
df1['Takes Reservations'] = np.where(df1['Takes Reservations']=='N/A',False,\
                                                df1['Takes Reservations'])
df1['Waiter Service'] = np.where(df1['Waiter Service']=='N/A',False,df1['Waiter Service'])
df1['Noise Level'] = np.where(df1['Noise Level']=='N/A','average',df1['Noise Level'])
df1['Outdoor Seating'] = np.where(df1['Outdoor Seating']=='N/A',False,df1['Outdoor Seating'])

In [20]:
# Normalizing user and item reviws to remove the scaling error
def  user_normalize_ratings(df):
    mean_rt = DataFrame({'avg_stars_user' : df.groupby( ['user_id'])['stars'].mean()}).reset_index()
    df = pd.merge(df,mean_rt,on='user_id')
    df['user_normalized_stars'] = df['stars']- df['avg_stars_user']
    return df
In [21]:
# Normalizing user and item reviws to remove the scaling error
def  item_normalize_ratings(df):
    mean_rt = DataFrame({'avg_stars_items' : df.groupby( ['business_id'])['stars'].mean()}).reset_index()
    df = pd.merge(df,mean_rt,on='business_id')
    df['item_normalized_stars'] = df['stars']- df['avg_stars_items']
    return df
In [22]:
review_LV_norm = review_LV[['business_id', 'user_id','stars','name']]
review_LV_norm = user_normalize_ratings(review_LV_norm)
review_LV_norm = item_normalize_ratings(review_LV_norm)

3.2 User - User collaborative filtering¶

In [48]:
#Train Model
item_bases_model = gl.item_similarity_recommender.create(review_LV_norm_sf_train, \
                                user_id='user_id', item_id='business_id', target='stars', similarity_type='pearson',verbose= False)

Recsys training: model = item_similarity

3.4 Content based recommender systems method¶

3.4.1. Generating restaurant attributes from reviews¶

3.4.1.1 Data preparation¶

In [ ]:
#### Join Restaurant and Review Data
restaurant_review = pd.merge(review_LV, restaurant_LV, how = 'inner',left_on =  'business_id', right_on = 'business_id')
#### Joining all the reviews for each business
restaurant_review = restaurant_review.groupby('business_id')['text'].apply(' '.join).reset_index()
restaurant_review = restaurant_review[['business_id','text']]
In [ ]:
#### Remove not useful characters from text
restaurant_review['text'] = restaurant_review.text.apply(lambda x: x.replace("\\",""))
restaurant_review['text'] = restaurant_review.text.apply(lambda x: x.replace(","," "))#.replace("\\","")
restaurant_review['text'] = restaurant_review.text.apply(lambda x: x.replace("\n\n"," "))#.replace("\\","")
restaurant_review['text'] = restaurant_review.text.apply(lambda x: x.replace("u'",""))#.replace("\\","")

3.4.1.2 Stemming and tokenizing the reviews¶

In [ ]:
from nltk.stem.porter import PorterStemmer
from nltk.tokenize import RegexpTokenizer


def stem_tokens(tokens, stemmer):
    stemmed = []
    for item in tokens:
        stemmed.append(stemmer.stem(item))
    return stemmed

def tokenize(text):
    tokenizer = RegexpTokenizer(r'([a-zA-Z]+)')
    tokens = tokenizer.tokenize(text)
    stemmer = PorterStemmer()
    stems = stem_tokens(tokens, stemmer)
    return stems

3.4.1.3 TF-IDF¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
tf = TfidfVectorizer(analyzer='word', ngram_range=(1,2), min_df = 0, stop_words = 'english',tokenizer=tokenize,max_features = 120)
In [ ]:
corpus = []
for line in sorted(restaurant_review.itertuples(), key=lambda t: int(t[0])):
    corpus.append(line[2])
In [ ]:
tfidf_matrix =  tf.fit_transform(corpus)
feature_names = tf.get_feature_names()
In [ ]:
tfidf_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(tfidf_matrix.todense(), columns = feature_names)
content_based_df = pd.merge(restaurant_review, tfidf_dataframe, left_on = 'business_id', right_on='business_id', how = 'left')
new_col = []
for col in content_based_df.columns.values:
    colx = col.replace (" ", "_")
    coly = colx.replace("-","_")
    new_col.append(coly)
    
content_based_df.columns = new_col
In [ ]:
#IMPUTING MISSING VALUES
#Some assumptions are made here hoping they will not have a major effect (low counts of missing values)

#content_based_df[content_based_df['Acc_credit_card'] == True]
content_based_df['Good_For'] = content_based_df['Good_For'].replace('N/A',0)
content_based_df['Acc_credit_card'] = content_based_df['Acc_credit_card'].replace('N/A',False)
content_based_df['Alcohol'] = content_based_df['Alcohol'].replace('N/A','unknown')
content_based_df['Ambience'] = content_based_df['Ambience'].replace('N/A',0)
content_based_df['Delivery'] = content_based_df['Delivery'].replace('N/A',False)
content_based_df['Parking'] = content_based_df['Parking'].fillna(0)
content_based_df['Price_Range'] = content_based_df['Price_Range'].replace('N/A',2.5)
content_based_df['Take_out'] = content_based_df['Take_out'].replace('N/A',False)
content_based_df['Takes_Reservations'] = content_based_df['Takes_Reservations'].replace('N/A',False)
content_based_df['Waiter_Service'] = content_based_df['Waiter_Service'].replace('N/A',False)
content_based_df['Noise_Level'] = content_based_df['Noise_Level'].replace('N/A','average')
content_based_df['Outdoor_Seating'] = content_based_df['Outdoor_Seating'].replace('N/A',False)

3.6 Matrix factorization with Factorization Machines¶

3.6.1 . Train model¶

In [72]:
mtrx_fctr_model = gl.recommender.factorization_recommender.create(observation_data = review_LV_norm_sf_train,\
                                             user_id='user_id',item_id='business_id',target ='stars',num_factors=12,\
                                             user_data= user_lv_sf_mf,\
                                              item_data = restaurants_LV_sf_mf ,verbose= False)

Recsys training: model = factorization_recommender

3.6.2 . Recommend restaurants and predict ratings¶

In [73]:
#Make Recommendations:
users = list(review_LV_norm_sf_train['user_id'].unique())
mtrx_fctr_recomm = mtrx_fctr_model.recommend(users=users,k=20,verbose= False)
mtrx_fctr_predict = mtrx_fctr_model.predict(review_LV_norm_sf_test)

3.7 Ranking matrix factorization with Factorization Machines¶

3.7.1 . Train model¶

In [76]:
rnkng_fctr_model = gl.recommender.ranking_factorization_recommender.create(observation_data = review_LV_norm_sf_train,\
                                             user_id='user_id',item_id='business_id',target ='stars',num_factors=12,\
                                                                           user_data= user_lv_sf_mf,\
                                              item_data = restaurants_LV_sf_mf,verbose= False)

Recsys training: model = ranking_factorization_recommender

3.7.2 . Recommend restaurants and predict ratings¶

In [77]:
#Make Recommendations:
users = list(review_LV_norm_sf_train['user_id'].unique())
rnkng_fctr_recomm = rnkng_fctr_model.recommend(users=users,k=20,verbose= False)
rnkng_fctr_predict = rnkng_fctr_model.predict(review_LV_norm_sf_test)

In [89]:
# Finding the most influential users who have are higher than the average for the following parameters.
inf_users = user_lv[(user_lv['review_count'] > np.mean(user_lv['review_count'])) &
                   (user_lv['average_stars'] > np.mean(user_lv['average_stars'])) &
                   (user_lv['fans'] > np.mean(user_lv['fans'])) &
                   (user_lv['useful'] > np.mean(user_lv['useful'])) &
                   (user_lv['funny'] > np.mean(user_lv['funny'])) &
                   (user_lv['cool'] > np.mean(user_lv['cool']))]
